name: Aaron
note: Aaron was the brother of Moses and the first high priest of the Israelites. He played a crucial role in the Exodus, assisting Moses in leading the people out of Egypt. Aaron's rod was used in various miracles, including the plagues of Egypt and the budding of the rod, signifying his divine appointment as high priest.

name: Abagtha
note: Abagtha was one of the seven eunuchs mentioned to have served King Ahasuerus of Persia.

name: Abda
note: Abda  is the father of Adoniram, who oversaw forced labor under King Solomon.

name: Abda
note: Abda is a Levite, the son of Shammua, who lived in Jerusalem after the Babylonian exile.

name: Abdeel
note: Abdeel was the father of Shelemiah and was involved in an attempt to arrest Jeremiah and Baruch at the command of King Jehoiakim, as recorded in Jeremiah 36:26.

name: Abdi
note: Abdi in 1 Chronicles 6:44 is the grandfather of Ethan, a Merarite, who was set over the service of song by David.

name: Abdi
note: Abdi in 2 Chronicles 29:12 is a Levite from the family of Merari who participated in the cleansing of the temple during Hezekiah’s reign.

name: Abdiel
note: Abdiel was a member of the tribe of Gad and is noted as the father of Ahi and the son of Guni. He lived in Gilead and Bashan during the reigns of King Jotham of Judah and King Jeroboam of Israel.

name: Abdon
note: Abdon, son of Hillel, was a judge of Israel who ruled for eight years. He was from Pirathon in the hill country of Ephraim. He had 40 sons and 30 grandsons who rode on 70 donkeys. He was buried in Pirathon in the land of Ephraim after his death.

name: Abdon
note: Abdon, son of Shashak, is mentioned as a descendant of Benjamin in 1 Chronicles 8:23.

name: Abdon
note: Abdon, son of Micah, served as an official during King Josiah’s reign and was sent by the king to consult the prophetess Huldah regarding the Book of the Law.

name: Abednego
note: Abednego, originally named Azariah, was one of the three Hebrew youths who stood firm in their faith and refused to worship King Nebuchadnezzar’s golden image. He, along with Shadrach and Meshach, was miraculously delivered from the fiery furnace by God.

name: Abel
note: Abel, the second son of Adam and Eve, was a righteous man who offered an acceptable sacrifice to God. His death at the hands of his brother Cain marked the first murder in human history. He is remembered in the New Testament for his faith and righteousness.

name: Abia
Abijah
Abiah
note: Abia is one of the 24 priestly divisions established by King David. Zechariah, the father of John the Baptist, belonged to this division.

name: Abia
Abijah
note: Abia, also known as Abijah, was the son of Rehoboam and king of Judah. He is part of the genealogy of Jesus Christ, as recorded in Matthew 1:7.

name: Abialbon
Abi-Albon
note: Abialbon, also referred to as Abi-Albon, was one of King David’s mighty warriors, known as one of 'the Thirty.' He is described as an Arbathite, indicating he was from the region of Arbath.

name: Abiasaph
Ebiasaph
note: Abiasaph, also referred to as Ebiasaph, was a descendant of Korah and part of the Levitical family. He is associated with the Korahite clans and is mentioned in genealogical records of the Levites.

name: Abiathar
note: Abiathar was the son of Ahimelech, a priest of Nob, and the only one to escape the massacre ordered by King Saul. He served as high priest during David's reign, often counseling David with the ephod. However, his support for Adonijah over Solomon led to his removal from the priesthood and exile to Anathoth. His story spans 1 Samuel, 2 Samuel, and 1 Kings, with a New Testament reference in Mark 2:26.

name: Abida
Abidah
note: Abida, or Abidah, was a son of Midian and grandson of Abraham through his concubine Keturah. He is mentioned in the genealogical lists of Abraham's descendants, indicating his role in the family line that led to the Midianite people.

name: Abidan
note: Abidan, the son of Gideoni, was a leader of the tribe of Benjamin during the Israelites' wilderness journey. He played a key role in the census, camp organization, and offerings at the Tabernacle, and was responsible for leading the tribe of Benjamin during the march.

name: Abiel
note: Abiel was a member of the tribe of Benjamin and the grandfather of King Saul. He is listed in the genealogies of Saul’s family in 1 Samuel 9:1 and 1 Chronicles 8:33 and 9:39 as the father of Ner and Kish.

name: Abiezer
note: Abiezer was a descendant of Manasseh, the son of Joseph, and an ancestor of Gideon. His descendants, the Abiezrites, played a prominent role in supporting Gideon during his campaign against the Midianites.

name: Abiezer the Anetothite
Abiezer the Antothite
note: Abiezer the Anetothite, also known as Abiezer the Antothite, was one of David’s mighty warriors and served as a captain in King David’s army. He commanded the ninth division of 24,000 men.

name: Abihu
note: Abihu, one of Aaron’s four sons, served as a priest of Israel. He is most known for the incident where he and his brother Nadab offered unauthorized fire before the Lord, leading to their deaths. This incident emphasized the strict requirements for priestly duties and the consequences of disobedience.
